# GraphQL — Mutation payload pattern

## Three fields together

Every mutation payload type exposes:

- `status: Boolean` (required) — `True` on success, `False` on failure
- `errors: JSONString` (required) — Python `dict` serialized to JSON; **`{}` on success**, never `null`
- One nullable resource field (`registration`, `user`, `verification`, etc.) — **`None` on failure**

## Graphene

```python
import graphene

class MyMutationPayload(graphene.ObjectType):
    status = graphene.Boolean(required=True)
    errors = graphene.JSONString(required=True)
    registration = graphene.Field(EventRegistrationType)
```

## Success / failure returns

```python
return MyMutationPayload(status=True, errors={}, registration=reg)

return MyMutationPayload(
    status=False,
    errors={"event_id": translate("errors", "event_not_found", language)},
    registration=None,
)
```

## Error keys

Use standardized keys when applicable: `email`, `password`, `token`, `permission`, `authentication`, `access_status`, `language`, `database`, `rate_limit`, `general`, or the GraphQL argument name for field-specific errors.

## i18n

All user-facing error **values** must come from `translate()` — never hardcoded English/French strings in production code (decorator edge cases may use fixed strings only if `language` is unavailable).

## HTTP

Business failures still return **HTTP 200**; the client checks `status` and `errors`, not the status code.

## Naming

Run Date mutations use `<app><Model><Action>` (camelCase), not `portal_*` prefixes.

